  "prompt": "What does a presidential censure look like?",
  "response": "A presidential censure is a formal statement of disapproval issued by a legislative body, typically within the context of the U.S. Congress. It is important to note that censure does not carry any legal penalties or remove the president from office; rather, it serves as a symbolic gesture denoting condemnation of the president's actions or behavior.\n\nThe process of censure generally involves the following steps:\n\n1. **Proposal**: Members of Congress (either from the House of Representatives or the Senate) introduce a resolution calling for censure. This resolution outlines the specific actions or conduct of the president that are being criticized.\n\n2. **Debate**: The resolution is then debated in the chamber where it was introduced. Members discuss the merits of the censure and the reasons for it.\n\n3. **Vote**: After debate, a vote is taken. A majority is required for the censure resolution to pass.\n\n4. **Formal Adoption**: If the resolution passes, it is formally adopted, and the president is officially censured. The censure may include a written statement that is made public.\n\n5. **Public Record**: The censure becomes part of the official congressional record, serving as a historical note on the president\u2019s conduct.\n\nHistorically, censure has been rare in U.S. history. While it has been proposed on several occasions, only a few U.S. presidents, such as Andrew Jackson and Bill Clinton, have faced formal censure actions. The ramifications of a censure are primarily political and can influence public opinion or subsequent congressional actions, but it does not have any legal consequences.",
